    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. So, if the supplier argues that the surge was a \"black swan\" event that couldn't have been prevented by standard maintenance, how does the burden of proof usually work? Basically, what exactly do they need to demonstrate to prove it wasn't just negligence or a foreseeable technical glitch?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In this scenario, the supplier would typically need to demonstrate that the power surge was truly an unexpected, rare event that fell below the threshold of what could be reasonably anticipated by a prudent business. They might present evidence to support the notion that the surge was an \"act of God\" or a naturally occurring occurrence, rather than a mere technical failure or negligence. The supplier's burden of proof is to show that the event was truly unforeseeable, rather than just a unfortunate or unusual occurrence.",
      "source": "target",
